But Cotta speaks in this passage as if Epicurus intended to prove the immortality of the gods from the inexhaustible mass of the atoms3 and in ἐξ 105-107 as is he used the ceaseless efllux of the divine images for the same purpose. That is certainly an error or an intentional misrepresenta· tion. Epicurus first assumed the immortality os the gods on account of the πρόληψις, and then tried to strengthen the belief by appealing to the law os isonomy. According to this law, in contrast with mortal beings, there must necessarily be immortal ones; and since all other beings of whom we have knowledge are mortal and transitory, the gods are the only ones remaining to whom we either can or must ascribe immortality.
